The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, April 23, 2004 				 SBI Caps office in London
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								Mumbai, April 22: SBI Capital Markets plans to expand its operations overseas by setting up base in London and Singapore.																								SBI Caps managing director and CEO Indrajit Gupta said it will set up an office in London by July, subject to regulatory approvals, and later in Singapore to seek new opportunities as Indian companies are striving for a global scale of operations.																								SBI Caps expansion plans are also aimed at adding foreign institutional investors to its list of clients.																								The leading investment banking outfit, which is owned 86 per cent by State Bank of India, today reported a 122 per cent rise in net profits to Rs 63.23 crore for the year ended March 31, 2004 against Rs 28.41 crore in 2002-03. 																								The companys gross income of Rs 142.75 crore is 18 per cent higher than the previous year.																								The board has recommended a 75 per cent dividend for 2003-04 (35 per cent for 2002-03). Gupta said the net profit and the dividend are the highest-ever announced by the company in 18 years of its existence.																								SBI Caps has started expanding its horizon both geographically and activity-wise. This may involve increasing our reach within the country and abroad, Gupta said.																								SBI Caps will set up an office in Guwahati and a few cities in the north to tap businesses from the government. The company is planning to expand its brokerage business further. 
